data.body:
I suspect the finalization process in MonoGame is broken.

Yes... the best way to work is for games to explicitly `Dispose` their resources.  However XNA does do finalization which destroys _unmanaged_ resources (like DirectX or OpenGL resources) which is critical to not leaking hardware resources which will not automatically cleanup otherwise.

Currently it seems we have the finalizer right.  [For example in GraphicsResource](https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsResource.cs#L71):

```
        ~GraphicsResource()
        {
            // Pass false so the managed objects are not released
            Dispose(false);
        }
```

That comment there is correct.  According to the XNA docs:

>  Finalize invokes Dispose(Boolean) with disposing set to false.
> http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb196223(v=xnagamestudio.31).aspx

So far so good.  However our `Dispose` methods seem to be wrong... [for example in Texture](https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/Texture.cs#L180):

```
        protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
        {
            if (!IsDisposed)
            {
#if DIRECTX
                if (disposing) // WRONG?
                {
                    SharpDX.Utilities.Dispose(ref _resourceView);
                    SharpDX.Utilities.Dispose(ref _texture);
                }
#elif OPENGL
```

Here you can see if `disposing` is false then the DirectX texture Resource or ShaderResourceView are not disposed.  Since these are wrappers around unmanaged hardware resources.... shouldn't we be disposing these when `disposing` is false?

Or is the point here that these wrappers need to be doing their own finalization which correctly frees the hardware resources?

I haven't debugged this but I'm running against the public 3.0.1 build and using the following code:

```
        SoundEffectInstanceFile.Play();
        if (SoundEffectInstanceFile.State != Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Audio.SoundState.Playing)
        {
            throw new Exception("Playing a sound doesn't put it in the Playing state");
        }
        SoundEffectInstanceFile.Pause();
        if (SoundEffectInstanceFile.State != Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Audio.SoundState.Paused)
        {
            throw new Exception("Pausing a sound doesn't put it in the Paused state");
        }
        SoundEffectInstanceFile.Play();
        if (SoundEffectInstanceFile.State != Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Audio.SoundState.Playing)
        {
            ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
            //////// THIS IS THE ONE THAT FAILS/////
            ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
            throw new Exception("Playing a sound doesn't put it in the Playing state");
        }
```

I'm testing the iOS platform through a remote build so the unit tests are failing reporting this.  This is a new test that I've added recently so I don't know if it has ever worked in MonoGame, but it does work in XNA 4.0
